Visitors admire the Liangdeng: Notes from the Field exhibition at the Minsheng Art Museum in Beijing. Photo: Courtesy of the Minsheng Art Museum Young Chinese artist Huang Yugang has transformed the exhibition hall at Beijing's Minsheng Art Museum into a field to showcase life in his home village of Liangdeng, Central China's Hunan Province.The Liangdeng: Notes from the Field exhibition showcases nearly 100 works from the artist, including oil and ink paintings, calligraphy  and installation works.  A small rice field has been relocated to the museum and will be returned upon the exhibition's completion. Huang stated that this field is the lifeblood of the people of Liangdeng and the source of his inspiration.  The exhibition explores how Huang's art connects the museum and the small village field.  The exhibition is scheduled to run until June 2. Chinese scientists design gene-editing tool using light to kill cancer cellsAbsence at PLA maritime parade will prevent US from learning about Chinese Navy: expertsChinese American organization condemns increasing racial profiling in US Actress Liu honored with Hollywood Walk of Fame starDelegation of HUST attends alumni gala in Los AngelesChinese driving Vegas growth